Why: patch 0007 deliberately leaks a non-quiesced instance's buffers (freeing
memory a running firmware instance still DMAs into hard-hangs the SoC), but the
release path then calls wave5_cleanup_instance, which unconditionally freed the
FBC/DPB framebuffers and the bitstream ring - exactly the buffers the firmware
writes - defeating the protection. The close paths now mark the instance
(keep_dma_bufs) whenever they bail without a successful quiesce (siblings live,
or the last-instance safety reset failed), and cleanup leaks those buffers too.

--- a/drivers/media/platform/chips-media/wave5/wave5-vpuapi.h
+++ b/drivers/media/platform/chips-media/wave5/wave5-vpuapi.h
@@ -818,6 +818,7 @@
 	bool cbcr_interleave;
 	bool nv21;
 	bool eos;
+	bool keep_dma_bufs;
 	struct vpu_buf bitstream_vbuf;
 	dma_addr_t last_rd_ptr;
 	size_t remaining_consumed_bytes;
--- a/drivers/media/platform/chips-media/wave5/wave5-vpuapi.c
+++ b/drivers/media/platform/chips-media/wave5/wave5-vpuapi.c
@@ -257,6 +257,7 @@
 			dev_warn(inst->dev->dev,
 				 "%s: instance still running with siblings live, leaking its buffers (no global reset)\n",
 				 __func__);
+			inst->keep_dma_bufs = true;
 			goto unlock_and_return;
 		}
 		dev_warn(inst->dev->dev, "%s: instance still running, VPU safety reset before free\n",
@@ -264,6 +265,7 @@
